  "enhanced_information": "Methylphenidate is the drug of choice for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), as it is a central nervous system stimulant that effectively increases attention span and reduces impulsivity, aligning with clinical guidelines that recommend stimulant medications as first-line treatments. Haloperidol, imipramine, and alprazolam are not typically used for ADHD; haloperidol is an antipsychotic, imipramine is a tricyclic antidepressant not recommended as first-line therapy, and alprazolam is a benzodiazepine not indicated for ADHD. Evidence supports that methylphenidate is FDA-approved for ADHD and is widely prescribed, confirming its status as the preferred choice."
